node.text:
Sometimes our innate gifts are more like riddles slowly revealing their deeper meaning over each chapter of our life with little regard for their immediate relevancy to the outside world. ⁣
⁣
Or they are like stars: guiding the recipient toward their highest potential. ⁣
⁣
— Sarah Elkhaldy⁣
⁣
⁣
✨Art by: @jetsyart ✨

⁣⁣
— Alan Watts⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣

⁣
⁣

node.text:
In the most ordinary terms, egolessness is a flexible identity. It manifests as inquisitiveness, as adaptability, as humor, as playfulness.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
— Pema Chödrön⁣⁣
⁣
⁣⁣
✨Art by:  @seamlessoo ✨⁣⁣

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Sarah Elkhaldy - The Alchemist on September 13, 2021 tagging @sscryp. May be an image of twilight, nature and cloud.

node.text:
It’s important that meditation is not seen as something that only happens when you are seated in a quiet place. Otherwise spirituality and our daily life become two separate things. That’s the primary confusion—that there is something called “my spiritual life,” and something called “my daily life.”⁣
⁣
— Adyashanti⁣
⁣
⁣
✨Art by: @sscryp ✨

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Sarah Elkhaldy - The Alchemist on September 09, 2021 tagging @seamlessoo. May be an image of sky and text.

node.text:
We cannot selectively numb emotions. When we numb the painful emotions, we also numb the positive emotions.⁣
⁣
 –Brené Brown⁣
⁣

The moment you have a centre, there must also be a circumference. But when the mind, being aware of the centre, also perceives the nature of the centre, that very perception is enough. To perceive the nature of the centre is the greatest thing you can do; it is the greatest action the mind can take. But that requires your complete attention.⁣
⁣
— Krishnamurti ⁣

I take my life as a web of relations viewed from a cen­ter. I feel this center—it is me. I call this center “I,” and it is from here that I think and feel. The notion of “I” takes up all the room, and comes back even in my better moments of work. In this it is always a single part of me that takes over—sometimes my thought, sometimes my emotion, perhaps my body. They never act together. There is no sense of the whole.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
To be centered means to release, for each part has to renounce the pretense that it is the whole, that it sees and directs the whole. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
— Jeanne de Salzmann⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
✨Art by: @natehill ✨

The understanding of the underlying emotion and its correct handling is, therefore, more rewarding and less time-consuming than dealing with one’s thoughts.⁣
⁣⁣
— David Hawkins⁣⁣
